Data Passing between components :

1) What is Lifting state up ?

Sibling components cannot communicate directly in react.Move the shared state to a nearest common parent and pass the state and callback functions down as props.
This pattern is called lifting state up.


2) When would you use Context API ?

When many components need access to the same State and passing the props to multiple intermediate components(State drilling) can be cumbersome.
Context API can be used to share data more efficiently.


3) Can a child modify props ?

No.Props are immutable. A child component should never changes props data.


4) How can a child update parent state ?

Pass a callback function from parent to child as a prop. Child will call the function, and parent will update it's own state.


5) Why can't child modify parent state directly ?

In react, data passes only in one-direction from parent to child. Making the application predictable and easy to debug.


6) What is Prop Drilling ?

If data is passed through every component. App -> Header -> NavBar -> Menu. It is called Prop Drilling.


7) What are the drawbacks of Prop Drilling ?

Extra boilerplate
Difficult maintenance
Intermediate components may not need the data


8) How do you avoid Prop Drilling ?

Context API
Redux
Zustand
Recoil


9) What is Context API ?

Context API allows to pass data through a component tree without passing props to each component.


10) Distinguish between State and Props ?

Props :

Passed from parent
External data
Immutable
Read-only

State :

Managed by component
Can be modified
React re-renders the component and it's descendents when the state is updated.
State can be updated by setter fucntion.


11) What is a controlled Component ?

const [name,setName] = React.useState("")

<input
  value={name}
  onChange={(e) => setName(e.target.value)}
/>

React controls the input value

12) What is a uncontrolled component ?

When the DOM itself manages the component.

<input defaultValue="Joe" /> or const formDate = new FormData(event.currentTarget)

